Data cleaning

data_cleaning.Rmd

There are several simple routines that can help make the preparation of civil registration data for tabulation less time consuming. This vignette uses the tidyverse suite of R packages to deal with common problems such as incorrect data types, duplicate rows, and missing values.

We will use a synthetic dataset that has the appearance of civil registration data to experiment with. The states of Nigeria are used but otherwise the data are completely fictional.

Our synthetic dataset

Before we start we need to load the tidyverse package.

library(tidyverse)

Then we can inspect our dataset.

glimpse(df)

#> Columns: 9

There are 9 variables in our data:

  • id
  • birth1a (Date of occurrence, Event)
  • birth1b (Date of registration, Event)
  • birth1c (Place of occurrence, Event)
  • birth1g (Type of birth, Event)
  • bith1h (Attendant at birth, Event)
  • birth1i (Type of place of occurrence, Event)
  • birth2a (Sex, Newborn)
  • birth3b (Age, Mother)

The variable birth1b is of type date, birth3b integer, and the others are all character.

Characters as dates

Dates can be inputted in a variety of formats such as â€œ1 August 24â€, Aug 1, 2024â€, and â€œ2024-08-01â€. Sometimes R will not be able to parse a date and will read it as a character.

The variable birth1a is a character but it should be a date. We can coerce it to a date by passing it to the as.Date() function and choosing the corresponding date format. birth1a follows the ISO 8601 standard for dates or â€˜YYYY-MM-DDâ€™ so we need to format the data with â€œ%Y-%m-%dâ€.

df <- mutate(df, birth1a = as.Date(birth1a, format = "%Y-%m-%d"))
class(df$birth1a)
#> [1] "Date"

Date formats in R

You can also use the ymd() function which more intuitively transforms the date into year, month, and day.

mutate(df, birth1a = ymd(birth1a))

Dates out of sequence

There may be inputting errors in the civil registration data such as the date of occurrence being recorded after the date of registration. To identify those records that are out of sync we can use a simple filter. The code below selects all of the rows where the date of occurrence is after the date of registration and counts them.

filter(df, birth1a > birth1b) |> 
  nrow()
#> [1] 540

Duplicate rows

We can identify duplicate rows by using the id variable which should be unique. The code below groups the data by id and then filters those with more than one row.

df |> 
  group_by(id) |> 
  filter(n()>1)
#> # A tibble: 11 Ã— 9

Characters as factors

It is common practice to read known values of a variable as characters, hence stringsAsFactors = FALSE. However, once you have read in the data you may wish to convert a character variable into a factor.

df$birth1g <- as_factor(df$birth1g)
class(df$birth1g)
#> [1] "factor"

Wrong order of levels

Sometimes the order of levels in a factor variable is not very helpful. The fct_relevel() function allows you to customise the order of levels. Here we reorder the values of birth1g (Type of birth) so that â€œQuadruplet or higherâ€ comes last.

df$birth1g |> levels()
#> [1] "Triplet"              "Twin"                 "Single"              
#> [4] "Quadruplet or higher"
df$birth1g |> fct_relevel("Single", "Twin", "Triplet", "Quadruplet or higher") |> levels()
#> [1] "Single"               "Twin"                 "Triplet"             
#> [4] "Quadruplet or higher"

Unhelpfully coded values

Sometimes values of a variable are coded unhelpfully. For example, the sex of a newborn baby may be recorded as â€œMâ€ and â€œFâ€ or 0 and 1.

df$birth2a |> levels()
#> NULL

We can easily recode these so that they are more readable. The fct_recode() function enables you to change factor levels by hand.

df$birth2a |> 
  fct_recode(Female = "F", Male = "M") |> 
  levels()
#> [1] "Female" "Male"

Missing data

Missing values are recorded in a variety of ways e.g.Â 999999, NULL, or even â€œâ€œ. For example, the place of occurrence might not be recorded and left blank. We can recode these missing values to a more explicit NA using the na_if() function.

df <- mutate(df, birth1c = na_if(birth1c, ""))

To identify how many missing values there are in each column we can run:

df |> map_dbl(~sum(is.na(.)))
#>      id birth1a birth1b birth1c birth1g birth1h birth1i birth2a birth3b 
#>       0       0       0      24       0       0     159       0       3

There are 24 NA values in birth1c, 159 in birth1i, and 3 in birth3b.

In cases where there are missing values in an integer variable we can impute them as an average. For example, there are 3 missing values in birth3b which is the age of the mother. We can impute the mean age with:

df <- df |> 
  mutate(birth3b = case_when(is.na(birth3b) ~ as.integer(mean(birth3b, na.rm = TRUE)), TRUE ~ birth3b))
